WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:23.218 align:middle line:90%


00:00:23.218 --> 00:00:24.700 align:middle line:90%
>>Robert Anton Wilson.

00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:33.592 align:middle line:90%


00:00:33.592 --> 00:00:38.070 align:middle line:84%
Robert Anton Wilson is
co-author with Robert Shea

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:42.090 align:middle line:84%
of the underground classic,
"The Illuminatus!" trilogy.

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:45.040 align:middle line:84%
His other writings include
"Schrodinger's Cat"

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:48.670 align:middle line:84%
trilogy called "the most
scientific of all science

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:50.600 align:middle line:90%
fiction novels."

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:55.230 align:middle line:84%
His novel "Illuminatus!" was
adapted as a one-hour science

00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:57.050 align:middle line:90%
fiction rock epic.

00:00:57.050 --> 00:00:57.970 align:middle line:90%
>>10-hour.

00:00:57.970 --> 00:00:59.100 align:middle line:90%
>>How many?

00:00:59.100 --> 00:00:59.600 align:middle line:90%
>>10-hour.

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:00.100 align:middle line:90%
>>10-hours.

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:03.300 align:middle line:90%


00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:07.620 align:middle line:84%
Bob, who sees himself
as a futurist,

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:10.242 align:middle line:84%
author, and now,
a sit-down comic.

00:01:10.242 --> 00:01:13.620 align:middle line:90%


00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:17.340 align:middle line:84%
Bob regularly gives
seminars at Esalen

00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:21.390 align:middle line:84%
and lectures at the Prophets
conferences around the world.

00:01:21.390 --> 00:01:24.180 align:middle line:84%
Let's give a big, warm welcome
to Robert Anton Wilson.

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:38.800 align:middle line:90%


00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:40.020 align:middle line:90%
>>That was very nice.

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:41.870 align:middle line:84%
If you kept on applauding
a little longer,

00:01:41.870 --> 00:01:43.703 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't have to think
of anything to say.

00:01:43.703 --> 00:01:47.100 align:middle line:90%
The time would get used up.

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:49.367 align:middle line:84%
It's true I once
described myself

00:01:49.367 --> 00:01:50.450 align:middle line:90%
as a guerrilla ontologist.

00:01:50.450 --> 00:01:53.020 align:middle line:90%


00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:56.110 align:middle line:90%
That was back in the '70s.

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:59.560 align:middle line:84%
In the '80s, I decided guerrilla
ontologist kept getting

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:03.440 align:middle line:90%
me confused with King Kong.

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:07.000 align:middle line:84%
So I started pronouncing it
as its original Spanish form,

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.430 align:middle line:90%
"gureeya" ontologist.

00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:12.380 align:middle line:84%
Nobody knew what the
hell I was talking about.

00:02:12.380 --> 00:02:14.940 align:middle line:84%
Then I read two
books in which I was

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:17.840 align:middle line:90%
described as a postmodernist.

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:20.870 align:middle line:84%
One was a sociological
textbook and the other

00:02:20.870 --> 00:02:23.480 align:middle line:84%
was a book of
literary criticism.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:26.170 align:middle line:84%
I figured if a literary
critic and a sociologist

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:28.390 align:middle line:84%
can both consider
me a postmodernist,

00:02:28.390 --> 00:02:31.660 align:middle line:84%
I might as well use
that as my label.

00:02:31.660 --> 00:02:33.890 align:middle line:84%
So I was calling
myself a postmodernist

00:02:33.890 --> 00:02:37.362 align:middle line:84%
for a while, until I read some
of the other postmodernists

00:02:37.362 --> 00:02:42.770 align:middle line:84%
and decided I didn't want to
be associated with them at all.

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:46.820 align:middle line:84%
So now I just call myself
a damned old crank,

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:48.960 align:middle line:84%
which I think covers the
situation much better

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:51.650 align:middle line:84%
than either of my
previous labels.

00:02:51.650 --> 00:02:54.160 align:middle line:84%
But if anybody wants to call
me a guerrilla ontologist,

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:55.330 align:middle line:90%
that's OK.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:57.584 align:middle line:90%
[GRUNTING]

00:02:57.584 --> 00:02:59.410 align:middle line:90%


00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:02.980 align:middle line:84%
Well, I'm supposed to be talking
about-- the title of my talk

00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:06.380 align:middle line:84%
is "The Universe
Contains a Maybe."

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:12.730 align:middle line:84%
And to start with, I'll take
off of where Dr. Kaku left off

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:15.820 align:middle line:90%
yesterday, Schrodinger's cat.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:19.870 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'm here
and maybe I'm not.

00:03:19.870 --> 00:03:24.110 align:middle line:84%
Which is to say, in some
eigenstates, I got here safely.

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:28.200 align:middle line:84%
In some eigenstates, the cab
carrying me here from the hotel

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:30.060 align:middle line:90%
crashed into a bread truck.

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:32.880 align:middle line:84%
And I got killed, and
I didn't get here.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.720 align:middle line:84%
Why are you seeing me? 'Cause
you're in one of the universes

00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:38.980 align:middle line:90%
where I did get here.

00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:41.520 align:middle line:84%
There's another universe
where you're all sitting here

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:43.860 align:middle line:84%
looking at an empty stage,
waiting to hear news

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:45.926 align:middle line:90%
about where the hell I am.

00:03:45.926 --> 00:03:49.740 align:middle line:84%
And I hope you would at least
have a slight pang of remorse

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:53.850 align:middle line:84%
when you heard about the bread
truck and my body scattered

00:03:53.850 --> 00:03:56.676 align:middle line:84%
all over Amsterdam
Avenue and all of that.

00:03:56.676 --> 00:03:59.580 align:middle line:90%


00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:01.980 align:middle line:84%
According to the
Everett-Wheeler-Graham

00:04:01.980 --> 00:04:06.200 align:middle line:84%
interpretation of the
Schrodinger's cat problem,

00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:08.650 align:middle line:84%
the cat's alive
in some universes

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:10.300 align:middle line:90%
and dead in other universes.

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:15.930 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't just apply to a
cat with a complicated trap

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:17.839 align:middle line:90%
that Schrodinger invented.

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:20.134 align:middle line:84%
Every time there's
a 0.5 probability,

00:04:20.134 --> 00:04:21.920 align:middle line:90%
the universe splits in two.

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:23.590 align:middle line:84%
And we get more
and more universes.

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:26.370 align:middle line:90%


00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:28.740 align:middle line:84%
You might be happy to
know, those of you who

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:32.520 align:middle line:84%
aren't really into
surrealism, that this only

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:34.200 align:middle line:90%
applies to possible universes.

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:37.330 align:middle line:90%


00:04:37.330 --> 00:04:39.885 align:middle line:84%
But if it's a possible
universe, it exists somewhere

00:04:39.885 --> 00:04:43.230 align:middle line:90%
in hyper space.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:47.840 align:middle line:84%
There's a universe where
Marilyn Monroe actually

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:50.790 align:middle line:84%
succeeded in persuading
John Kennedy to divorce

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:52.890 align:middle line:90%
Jackie and marry her.

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:55.740 align:middle line:90%
And she became First Lady.

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.857 align:middle line:84%
I wish I had lived in
that universe instead

00:04:57.857 --> 00:05:00.610 align:middle line:90%
of the mess we're in now.

00:05:00.610 --> 00:05:02.380 align:middle line:84%
In that universe,
the whole world

00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:04.790 align:middle line:84%
might have become
a lot more liberal.

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:06.700 align:middle line:84%
And I could have got a
little bit of cocaine

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:08.934 align:middle line:84%
this morning to wake
me up before performing

00:05:08.934 --> 00:05:10.326 align:middle line:90%
at this ungodly hour.

00:05:10.326 --> 00:05:13.580 align:middle line:90%


00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:16.520 align:middle line:84%
As it is, I'm stuck
in a universe where

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:18.565 align:middle line:84%
a crackhead in the
White House could throw

00:05:18.565 --> 00:05:22.720 align:middle line:84%
all the poor crackheads in jail
and has hired somebody tougher

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:26.430 align:middle line:84%
than the previous czar
to carry that out.

00:05:26.430 --> 00:05:29.516 align:middle line:84%
Who the hell wants to live
in a universe like that?

00:05:29.516 --> 00:05:34.360 align:middle line:90%


00:05:34.360 --> 00:05:36.110 align:middle line:84%
Of course, that
may be just a libel

00:05:36.110 --> 00:05:37.807 align:middle line:90%
spread by the Democratic party.

00:05:37.807 --> 00:05:41.630 align:middle line:84%
Maybe George isn't
a crackhead anymore.

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:43.470 align:middle line:84%
There's a website
that sells buttons

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:47.542 align:middle line:84%
with a picture of George,
His Fraudulency George II.

00:05:47.542 --> 00:05:49.490 align:middle line:84%
They have a button
with a picture of him,

00:05:49.490 --> 00:05:52.140 align:middle line:84%
and it says, "Not a
crackhead anymore."

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:54.350 align:middle line:90%
Doesn't that cheer you up?

00:05:54.350 --> 00:06:01.100 align:middle line:84%
That kind of cheers me
up, sort of, in a way.

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:03.342 align:middle line:90%
I loved the last election.

00:06:03.342 --> 00:06:05.050 align:middle line:84%
It was the first time
in American history

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:07.860 align:middle line:84%
we had to choose between a
pothead who claimed he was not

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:10.870 align:middle line:84%
a pothead anymore and
a crackhead who claimed

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:13.480 align:middle line:90%
he was not a crackhead anymore.

00:06:13.480 --> 00:06:15.760 align:middle line:84%
And the public was so
damn confused that nobody

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.070 align:middle line:90%
knows who won the election.

00:06:17.070 --> 00:06:19.735 align:middle line:90%


00:06:19.735 --> 00:06:23.140 align:middle line:84%
As Mr. Justice Stevens
said, "We will never

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:26.320 align:middle line:84%
know with certainty who
won this year's election.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:28.690 align:middle line:90%
But we do know the loser.

00:06:28.690 --> 00:06:30.610 align:middle line:84%
The loser is the
public's confidence

00:06:30.610 --> 00:06:34.760 align:middle line:90%
in the integrity of our judges."

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.290 align:middle line:84%
That's not a very
funny line, is it?

00:06:37.290 --> 00:06:40.090 align:middle line:84%
Well, stop and think about
it for a while though.

00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:45.570 align:middle line:84%
John Adams, our second
president, wrote in a letter

00:06:45.570 --> 00:06:47.950 align:middle line:84%
to Thomas Jefferson, who
you may have heard of,

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:50.740 align:middle line:90%
he was our third president.

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:53.570 align:middle line:84%
Adams wrote to Jefferson,
"I cannot consider political

00:06:53.570 --> 00:06:57.310 align:middle line:84%
history seriously without
either weeping or laughing.

00:06:57.310 --> 00:06:59.140 align:middle line:90%
I prefer to laugh."

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:00.930 align:middle line:90%
And that's the way I look at it.

00:07:00.930 --> 00:07:03.680 align:middle line:84%
If we got a crackhead in
the White House, well,

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:05.170 align:middle line:90%
I think that's pretty funny.

00:07:05.170 --> 00:07:06.800 align:middle line:84%
That's the next
best thing to having

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:08.464 align:middle line:90%
Harpo Marx in the White House.

00:07:08.464 --> 00:07:16.060 align:middle line:90%


00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:17.783 align:middle line:90%
As for getting back to maybe.

00:07:17.783 --> 00:07:20.310 align:middle line:90%


00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:22.580 align:middle line:84%
I think I had a few
more anti-Bush jokes,

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:24.210 align:middle line:84%
but they just
slipped from my mind.

00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:26.740 align:middle line:84%
At this hour in the
morning, my memory

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:29.530 align:middle line:84%
is not functioning
as well as my tongue.

00:07:29.530 --> 00:07:32.700 align:middle line:84%
I can talk, but I can't think
about what I'm talking about.

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:33.960 align:middle line:90%
But oh well.

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:35.985 align:middle line:84%
I think I've had that
problem for years.

00:07:35.985 --> 00:07:39.630 align:middle line:90%


00:07:39.630 --> 00:07:42.490 align:middle line:84%
I have found a way to get
high and stay spaced out

00:07:42.490 --> 00:07:45.630 align:middle line:84%
for hours on end,
and the government

00:07:45.630 --> 00:07:47.970 align:middle line:90%
can't take it away from me.

00:07:47.970 --> 00:07:48.933 align:middle line:90%
It's called senility.

00:07:48.933 --> 00:07:53.190 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:57.950 align:middle line:90%
And there are four major traits.

00:07:57.950 --> 00:08:00.620 align:middle line:90%
Increase in long-term memory.

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:03.690 align:middle line:84%
I can wheel myself to the
kitchen when I'm home.

00:08:03.690 --> 00:08:06.840 align:middle line:84%
And on the way, I can remember
a fistfight I had with a kid

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:11.540 align:middle line:84%
named Billy Batson in
kindergarten, 65 years ago.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:14.020 align:middle line:84%
And I can even remember
my life in the womb.

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:15.980 align:middle line:84%
And I can remember
back to when I

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:18.730 align:middle line:84%
was swinging through the
trees with the other apes.

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:21.750 align:middle line:84%
I can remember back
to being a fish.

00:08:21.750 --> 00:08:26.190 align:middle line:84%
All evolution opens up before
me in an endlessly retreating

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:29.640 align:middle line:90%
abyss of timeless time.

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:31.320 align:middle line:84%
And then when I
get to the kitchen,

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:34.584 align:middle line:84%
the second effect takes over, a
decrease in short-term memory.

00:08:34.584 --> 00:08:38.350 align:middle line:84%
I can't remember what I
went to the kitchen for.

00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:39.850 align:middle line:90%
I look around, what the hell?

00:08:39.850 --> 00:08:42.858 align:middle line:84%
What am I doing
in this room now?

00:08:42.858 --> 00:08:45.080 align:middle line:90%
I thought I was at the computer.

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:46.900 align:middle line:90%
And the third effect.

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:50.370 align:middle line:90%


00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:52.120 align:middle line:84%
I don't remember what
the third effect is.

00:08:52.120 --> 00:08:57.690 align:middle line:90%


00:08:57.690 --> 00:09:00.200 align:middle line:84%
And the fourth is I don't
give a fuck anymore.

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:11.560 align:middle line:90%


00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:15.000 align:middle line:90%
The Chinese have a proverb.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.560 align:middle line:84%
I got a friend who just got
his PhD in Chinese language

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:19.306 align:middle line:90%
and literature.

00:09:19.306 --> 00:09:20.680 align:middle line:84%
And I quoted this
proverb to him.

00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:22.280 align:middle line:84%
And he said he
heard it many times,

00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:25.370 align:middle line:84%
but he didn't know where it
came from or who invented it.

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:28.770 align:middle line:84%
He's got a Chinese
wife, raised in Taiwan.

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:29.780 align:middle line:90%
And she's heard it too.

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:32.090 align:middle line:84%
She doesn't know
who invented it.

00:09:32.090 --> 00:09:33.970 align:middle line:90%
So I guess it's a folk proverb.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:35.870 align:middle line:90%
There's no known author.

00:09:35.870 --> 00:09:39.210 align:middle line:84%
It says, "The wise are
Confucian in good times,

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:43.540 align:middle line:84%
Buddhist in bad times,
and Taoist in old age."

00:09:43.540 --> 00:09:47.030 align:middle line:10%
Now the Confucians try
to improve society.

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:48.550 align:middle line:84%
The Buddhists say,
that's hopeless.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:50.080 align:middle line:90%
Just try to improve yourself.

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:53.160 align:middle line:84%
And the Taoists say,
I don't give a fuck.

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:55.800 align:middle line:10%
So you see, between
senility and Taoism,

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:59.500 align:middle line:10%
I have arrived at a
remarkable tranquility.

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.760 align:middle line:10%
Every time Bush
finds a new excuse

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:04.005 align:middle line:10%
to bomb someplace, instead
of weeping, I laugh.

00:10:04.005 --> 00:10:07.100 align:middle line:10%
Oh well, what can you
expect of a species

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:10.170 align:middle line:10%
of domesticated primates but
except the alpha males will

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:14.130 align:middle line:10%
be the ugliest and meanest
ones in the whole damn tribe?

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:16.360 align:middle line:84%
It's part of the
evolutionary script, I think.

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:20.951 align:middle line:90%


00:10:20.951 --> 00:10:21.450 align:middle line:90%
Maybe.

00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:25.990 align:middle line:90%


00:10:25.990 --> 00:10:30.920 align:middle line:84%
I would like to argue,
or propose, or cogitate,

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:35.105 align:middle line:84%
or ruminate, or
blabber to the effect

00:10:35.105 --> 00:10:39.290 align:middle line:84%
that if everybody used the
word "maybe" more often,

00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:41.600 align:middle line:84%
the whole human race might
suddenly become stark,

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:45.410 align:middle line:90%
staring sane.

00:10:45.410 --> 00:10:48.030 align:middle line:84%
Just imagine if
every time you turn

00:10:48.030 --> 00:10:50.200 align:middle line:84%
to the high channels
on your TV set,

00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:53.225 align:middle line:84%
you'd catch Pat Robertson,
or Jerry Falwell,

00:10:53.225 --> 00:10:59.150 align:middle line:84%
or one of those weird people
proclaiming, I tell you,

00:10:59.150 --> 00:11:02.325 align:middle line:84%
brethren, maybe Jesus
was the Son of God.

00:11:02.325 --> 00:11:05.310 align:middle line:90%


00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:08.530 align:middle line:84%
Imagine if you travel through
the Mid-East and every muezzin

00:11:08.530 --> 00:11:13.220 align:middle line:84%
was howling from the parapets,
maybe Allah is the only god,

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:16.870 align:middle line:84%
and maybe Muhammad
is his prophet.

00:11:16.870 --> 00:11:20.280 align:middle line:84%
Imagine if the Israelis
were going around chanting,

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:22.770 align:middle line:84%
maybe God gave us
this land, and we

00:11:22.770 --> 00:11:24.160 align:middle line:90%
can clean off the aborigines.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:27.790 align:middle line:90%


00:11:27.790 --> 00:11:29.980 align:middle line:84%
Imagine, as the
parapsychologists were saying,

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:33.360 align:middle line:84%
maybe this proves the
existence of psy powers.

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:35.170 align:middle line:84%
And CSICOP was
going around saying,

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:39.880 align:middle line:84%
maybe their laboratory methods
were not strict enough.

00:11:39.880 --> 00:11:41.480 align:middle line:84%
Imagine if all the
communists that

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:44.270 align:middle line:84%
are left in the world,
all seven of them said,

00:11:44.270 --> 00:11:46.350 align:middle line:84%
maybe we need a
violent revolution

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:48.286 align:middle line:90%
to overthrow capitalism.

00:11:48.286 --> 00:11:50.660 align:middle line:84%
Imagine if all the conservatives
are going around saying,

00:11:50.660 --> 00:11:53.590 align:middle line:84%
maybe we got the best
economic system in the world

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:55.160 align:middle line:84%
even though most
of our population

00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:57.695 align:middle line:84%
is living on the streets and
nobody gets adequate health

00:11:57.695 --> 00:11:58.380 align:middle line:90%
care.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:11:59.590 align:middle line:90%
But maybe it's the best.

00:11:59.590 --> 00:12:01.300 align:middle line:84%
Maybe humanity can't
do better than this

00:12:01.300 --> 00:12:02.700 align:middle line:90%
because of original sin.

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:04.159 align:middle line:90%
Maybe.

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:05.950 align:middle line:84%
If everybody was going
around saying maybe,

00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:10.080 align:middle line:84%
think of how fewer violent
quarrels we'd have.

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:12.140 align:middle line:84%
I've seen some pretty
violent quarrels

00:12:12.140 --> 00:12:15.100 align:middle line:84%
between parapsychologists
and members of CSICOP

00:12:15.100 --> 00:12:17.550 align:middle line:84%
because none of
them ever say maybe.

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:20.325 align:middle line:84%
The parapsychologists
say, we have proven this.

00:12:20.325 --> 00:12:23.580 align:middle line:84%
And the CSICOPs say,
you haven't proven it.

00:12:23.580 --> 00:12:24.670 align:middle line:90%
And they got an out too.

00:12:24.670 --> 00:12:27.340 align:middle line:84%
They got this
wonderful clause, which

00:12:27.340 --> 00:12:32.290 align:middle line:84%
is, "An extraordinary claim
demands extraordinary proof."

00:12:32.290 --> 00:12:35.029 align:middle line:84%
Now you could use that against
every argument you hear.

00:12:35.029 --> 00:12:36.570 align:middle line:84%
No matter what
anybody says, you say,

00:12:36.570 --> 00:12:37.944 align:middle line:84%
that's an
extraordinary argument.

00:12:37.944 --> 00:12:40.190 align:middle line:90%
I demand extraordinary proof.

00:12:40.190 --> 00:12:43.010 align:middle line:84%
What the fuck is
extraordinary proof?

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:45.980 align:middle line:84%
Why can't ordinary
proof handle the matter?

00:12:45.980 --> 00:12:47.990 align:middle line:84%
But you keep asking for
extraordinary proof,

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:50.960 align:middle line:90%
nobody can ever produce it.

00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:55.600 align:middle line:84%
But "maybe" can be a
very powerful word,

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:59.050 align:middle line:84%
especially if you use some
of Korzybski's other devices

00:12:59.050 --> 00:13:04.180 align:middle line:84%
to moderate overly dogmatic
Indo-European languages.

00:13:04.180 --> 00:13:10.150 align:middle line:84%
For instance, John is
grouchy and irritable.

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:12.920 align:middle line:84%
That's the kind of sentence
you hear all the time.

00:13:12.920 --> 00:13:17.530 align:middle line:84%
Suppose somebody said, maybe
John is grouchy and irritable.

00:13:17.530 --> 00:13:19.190 align:middle line:84%
Then you might be
ready to accept

00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:22.900 align:middle line:84%
the fact that John isn't grouchy
and irritable all the time.

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:25.335 align:middle line:84%
Or if you used
Korzybski's dating

00:13:25.335 --> 00:13:30.060 align:middle line:84%
and-- has anybody here ever
hear of Korzybski, by the way?

00:13:30.060 --> 00:13:31.310 align:middle line:90%
Hey, what a literate audience.

00:13:31.310 --> 00:13:34.460 align:middle line:84%
I think I saw 10 hands
out in the crowd.

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:37.750 align:middle line:84%
Alfred Korzybski was
a Polish mathematician

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:41.330 align:middle line:84%
who proposed the two-valued
Aristotelian either-or

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:44.620 align:middle line:84%
logic does not fit the
universe we live in.

00:13:44.620 --> 00:13:46.200 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, we
should abandon it

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:49.520 align:middle line:84%
and use a more flexible
logic, which he

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:52.440 align:middle line:90%
called infinite-valued logic.

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:56.390 align:middle line:84%
Now this is an outgrowth
on Neumann's maybe.

00:13:56.390 --> 00:13:59.510 align:middle line:84%
Neumann and his book
on quantum mechanics

00:13:59.510 --> 00:14:01.670 align:middle line:84%
handle the Schrodinger's
cat paradox

00:14:01.670 --> 00:14:04.060 align:middle line:84%
by saying the cat can
be in three states--

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:07.500 align:middle line:84%
dead, which is 0;
alive, which is 1;

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:10.110 align:middle line:90%
and a half, which is maybe.

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:13.125 align:middle line:84%
And the cat is in the maybe
state until we open the door,

00:14:13.125 --> 00:14:16.830 align:middle line:90%
as Dr. Kaku explained yesterday.

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:20.110 align:middle line:84%
And that makes a lot of sense
mathematically because until we

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:22.630 align:middle line:84%
open the door, the cat
is in a maybe state.

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:24.586 align:middle line:84%
"In the math that's
in our head, the cat

00:14:24.586 --> 00:14:26.530 align:middle line:90%
is both alive and dead."

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:32.510 align:middle line:84%
Quoting my favorite poet--
that's myself, by the way.

00:14:32.510 --> 00:14:40.490 align:middle line:84%
That's from my novel,
"Schrodinger's Cat."

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:43.220 align:middle line:84%
"In every random
quantum state, the cat

00:14:43.220 --> 00:14:47.320 align:middle line:84%
remains suspended state in
some quantum eigenstate.

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:49.840 align:middle line:84%
In precisely half the
cases, that's 0.5,

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:52.030 align:middle line:90%
the cat is both dead and alive."

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:53.520 align:middle line:90%
No, I can't quote my own poetry.

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:54.770 align:middle line:90%
It's too early in the morning.

00:14:54.770 --> 00:14:57.295 align:middle line:84%
I keep losing the meter and
putting in the wrong words.

00:14:57.295 --> 00:15:01.650 align:middle line:90%


00:15:01.650 --> 00:15:03.010 align:middle line:90%
Suppose we met two people.

00:15:03.010 --> 00:15:04.860 align:middle line:84%
And one said, John is
grouchy and irritable.

00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:06.955 align:middle line:84%
And the other said,
John is cheerful

00:15:06.955 --> 00:15:10.470 align:middle line:84%
and makes everybody
else cheerful too.

00:15:10.470 --> 00:15:13.100 align:middle line:84%
That leads us into a state of
perpetual, which one of them

00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:14.925 align:middle line:90%
is inaccurate?

00:15:14.925 --> 00:15:17.425 align:middle line:84%
Well, in our language, one of
them has got to be inaccurate.

00:15:17.425 --> 00:15:20.310 align:middle line:84%
Our traditional
Indo-European language

00:15:20.310 --> 00:15:23.790 align:middle line:84%
has codified it to
Aristotelian logic.

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:26.990 align:middle line:84%
But if we throw in a maybe and
date, and index our statement,

00:15:26.990 --> 00:15:31.265 align:middle line:84%
we might come out with something
like, John seemed to me grouchy

00:15:31.265 --> 00:15:34.024 align:middle line:84%
and irritable at
the office all week.

00:15:34.024 --> 00:15:35.440 align:middle line:84%
And the other one
might be saying,

00:15:35.440 --> 00:15:37.160 align:middle line:84%
John seemed very
cheerful and made

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.930 align:middle line:84%
everybody else cheerful at
the beach on the weekend.

00:15:40.930 --> 00:15:43.190 align:middle line:84%
Now the statements don't
contradict each other at all

00:15:43.190 --> 00:15:46.345 align:middle line:84%
because we've modified them
by adding more information

00:15:46.345 --> 00:15:50.220 align:middle line:84%
and dropping out the "is"
and putting in "seems to me."

00:15:50.220 --> 00:15:54.579 align:middle line:84%
How many times have you
heard people arguing?

00:15:54.579 --> 00:15:56.745 align:middle line:84%
Well, maybe you don't hang
out with the same circles

00:15:56.745 --> 00:15:58.600 align:middle line:90%
that I do.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:15:59.700 align:middle line:90%
Well, let's try it.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:00.760 align:middle line:84%
How many times have
you heard people

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:02.468 align:middle line:84%
arguing about whether
Beethoven is better

00:16:02.468 --> 00:16:07.060 align:middle line:84%
than Mozart or Mozart is
better than Beethoven?

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:10.760 align:middle line:84%
Or the Iron Butterfly is
better than the Sex Pistols.

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:14.170 align:middle line:84%
No, the Sex Pistols are better
than the Iron Butterfly.

00:16:14.170 --> 00:16:16.320 align:middle line:84%
That gives you an idea how
much I know about rock.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:19.800 align:middle line:84%
Both of those examples come
from the '60s and '70s.

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:21.505 align:middle line:84%
Let's go back to
Mozart and Beethoven

00:16:21.505 --> 00:16:25.230 align:middle line:84%
where I know a little about
what I'm talking about.

00:16:25.230 --> 00:16:28.760 align:middle line:84%
Now if we were to try to talk in
operational functional language

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:30.784 align:middle line:84%
like scientists do
about their instruments,

00:16:30.784 --> 00:16:32.200 align:middle line:84%
we have to include
the instrument.

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:34.740 align:middle line:84%
The instrument is
my nervous system.

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:37.370 align:middle line:84%
So before I can get to an
argument about whether Mozart

00:16:37.370 --> 00:16:39.730 align:middle line:84%
is better than Beethoven
or Beethoven is better

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:41.480 align:middle line:84%
than Mozart, I'd have
to reformulate it

00:16:41.480 --> 00:16:45.550 align:middle line:84%
into language that includes the
instrument and the observer.

00:16:45.550 --> 00:16:47.930 align:middle line:84%
So I'd have to say,
in my present mixed

00:16:47.930 --> 00:16:53.470 align:middle line:84%
state of musical
knowledge and ignorance,

00:16:53.470 --> 00:16:56.730 align:middle line:84%
Beethoven seems better
to be than Mozart.

00:16:56.730 --> 00:16:59.860 align:middle line:84%
That might even influence
the guy or the girl

00:16:59.860 --> 00:17:01.590 align:middle line:84%
on the other side
of the argument

00:17:01.590 --> 00:17:04.160 align:middle line:84%
to say, well, in my
present state of mixed

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:07.300 align:middle line:84%
musical ignorance and knowledge,
Mozart seems a hell of a lot

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:09.140 align:middle line:90%
better than Beethoven to me.

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:10.859 align:middle line:84%
What have we got
left to argue about?

00:17:10.859 --> 00:17:13.339 align:middle line:84%
We're not arguing about
Mozart and Beethoven at all.

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:15.130 align:middle line:84%
We're arguing about
our own nervous systems

00:17:15.130 --> 00:17:18.169 align:middle line:90%
and how they apprehend music.

00:17:18.169 --> 00:17:19.960 align:middle line:84%
And yet most of the
time, we get into these

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:22.290 align:middle line:84%
is arguments as if we're
talking about something

00:17:22.290 --> 00:17:26.040 align:middle line:90%
that doesn't include ourselves.

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:29.440 align:middle line:84%
There's an old Sufi story which
you will not disappoint me

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:30.700 align:middle line:90%
if you don't laugh at it.

00:17:30.700 --> 00:17:34.370 align:middle line:84%
Nobody ever does laugh at it,
but I still like to use it.

00:17:34.370 --> 00:17:37.630 align:middle line:84%
Nasreddin, the wisest
man in all Islam,

00:17:37.630 --> 00:17:40.662 align:middle line:84%
was seen racing through
the streets of Baghdad.

00:17:40.662 --> 00:17:42.120 align:middle line:84%
This was several
hundred years ago,

00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:45.940 align:middle line:84%
so he wasn't trying to get
away from American bombers.

00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:50.170 align:middle line:84%
He's racing around on his
donkey through every palazzo,

00:17:50.170 --> 00:17:55.070 align:middle line:84%
and alley, and street, and
every place he could race.

00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:57.740 align:middle line:84%
And people came out, what
is Nasreddin looking for?

00:17:57.740 --> 00:18:00.720 align:middle line:84%
So finally, they started running
out to him, going, Nasreddin,

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:02.420 align:middle line:90%
what are you looking for?

00:18:02.420 --> 00:18:07.360 align:middle line:84%
And Nasreddin yelled back,
I'm looking for my donkey.

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:10.050 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I got a laugh that time.

00:18:10.050 --> 00:18:14.670 align:middle line:10%
The donkey represents what
we're all looking for,

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:17.840 align:middle line:10%
the answer to all of the
mysteries of the universe,

00:18:17.840 --> 00:18:20.190 align:middle line:10%
the mysteries of emotional
life, the mysteries

00:18:20.190 --> 00:18:22.280 align:middle line:10%
of intellectual life,
the mysteries of being

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:23.380 align:middle line:10%
a human being.

00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:25.370 align:middle line:90%
We look for it everywhere.

00:18:25.370 --> 00:18:28.470 align:middle line:84%
And it's carrying us around
all the time like the donkey

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:32.060 align:middle line:90%
that Nasreddin lost track of.

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:34.930 align:middle line:84%
In my workshops,
when I do a workshop,

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:37.320 align:middle line:84%
I usually have the
people describe the hall

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:39.487 align:middle line:90%
outside the workshop room.

00:18:39.487 --> 00:18:41.820 align:middle line:84%
I have everybody write out a
list of what they remember.

00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:45.100 align:middle line:84%
No two lists are alike,
which illustrates what

00:18:45.100 --> 00:18:47.940 align:middle line:90%
I call neurological relativism.

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:51.550 align:middle line:84%
No two people ever pass
through the same hallway.

00:18:51.550 --> 00:18:53.670 align:middle line:84%
Each one creates a different
hallway in their head

00:18:53.670 --> 00:18:56.440 align:middle line:84%
which they think is
the real hallway.

00:18:56.440 --> 00:18:59.200 align:middle line:84%
Just like everybody
thinks Mozart is better

00:18:59.200 --> 00:19:01.780 align:middle line:84%
than Beethoven or Beethoven
is better than Mozart.

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:04.200 align:middle line:84%
Except for the
wisenheimers who claim

00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:06.080 align:middle line:84%
Wagner is better
than either of them.

00:19:06.080 --> 00:19:08.680 align:middle line:84%
But we can do without
them, can't we?

00:19:08.680 --> 00:19:11.455 align:middle line:84%
Now if there's any Wagnerians in
the audience, I'm only kidding.

00:19:11.455 --> 00:19:11.955 align:middle line:90%
Honest.

00:19:11.955 --> 00:19:19.360 align:middle line:90%


00:19:19.360 --> 00:19:21.890 align:middle line:84%
The funny thing
about these lists,

00:19:21.890 --> 00:19:24.700 align:middle line:84%
after we compare them, it turns
out the person with the longest

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:27.910 align:middle line:84%
list, it's always about
half as long as the list

00:19:27.910 --> 00:19:30.880 align:middle line:84%
we get by putting all
the other lists together.

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:33.900 align:middle line:84%
Which indicates the most
observant person, the Sherlock

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:36.560 align:middle line:84%
Holmes in the
group, observes half

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:39.790 align:middle line:84%
of what the whole audience
as a group observes.

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:42.050 align:middle line:84%
So you can always learn
something from everybody else

00:19:42.050 --> 00:19:44.350 align:middle line:84%
no matter how dumb or
wrongheaded they seem.

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:45.920 align:middle line:84%
If you listen to
them closely enough,

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:49.430 align:middle line:84%
they know something
you don't know.

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:51.430 align:middle line:84%
So it's worth
listening to everybody.

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:57.660 align:middle line:84%
When I was a wee tot
back in the last ice age,

00:19:57.660 --> 00:20:00.710 align:middle line:84%
dinosaurs still
roamed the Earth.

00:20:00.710 --> 00:20:04.240 align:middle line:90%
Roosevelt was president.

00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:08.170 align:middle line:90%
It was rugged times.

00:20:08.170 --> 00:20:12.890 align:middle line:84%
It cost a whole goddamn
dime to go to the movies.

00:20:12.890 --> 00:20:17.100 align:middle line:84%
And all you got was an A
movie, a B movie, a travel log,

00:20:17.100 --> 00:20:23.040 align:middle line:84%
a cartoon, a "Three Stooges"
comedy, and a news reel,

00:20:23.040 --> 00:20:24.070 align:middle line:90%
and a candy bar.

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:26.640 align:middle line:90%


00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:31.220 align:middle line:84%
And back in those days, nobody
but the extreme right-wing

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:34.150 align:middle line:84%
Republicans, the most
reactionary bastards

00:20:34.150 --> 00:20:37.010 align:middle line:84%
in the country, said, once
they give you a Social Security

00:20:37.010 --> 00:20:38.800 align:middle line:84%
number, they'll
keep track of you.

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:41.200 align:middle line:90%
They'll know everything you do.

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:42.630 align:middle line:90%
There will be no privacy left.

00:20:42.630 --> 00:20:45.140 align:middle line:90%
It'll be like Nazi Germany.

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:47.460 align:middle line:90%
How can anybody be that crazy?

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:51.345 align:middle line:84%
We've had Social Security
numbers for over 60 years now.

00:20:51.345 --> 00:20:53.470 align:middle line:84%
And they're not keeping
track of everything you do.

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:54.595 align:middle line:90%
They don't have everything.

00:20:54.595 --> 00:20:57.370 align:middle line:84%
You can cash a check without
putting your Social Security

00:20:57.370 --> 00:20:58.050 align:middle line:90%
number on it.

00:20:58.050 --> 00:20:59.687 align:middle line:90%
Well, no, you can't.

00:20:59.687 --> 00:21:01.520 align:middle line:84%
You could order something
over the internet.

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:03.430 align:middle line:84%
No, you gotta give them
your Social Security number.

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:05.596 align:middle line:84%
Well, actually, they do
know everything we're doing,

00:21:05.596 --> 00:21:06.500 align:middle line:90%
don't they?

00:21:06.500 --> 00:21:08.690 align:middle line:84%
Besides, they've
got satellites now

00:21:08.690 --> 00:21:10.620 align:middle line:84%
that can read the
headline on a newspaper

00:21:10.620 --> 00:21:13.120 align:middle line:84%
if you open a newspaper
on the street.

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:14.750 align:middle line:84%
They've got
heat-sensitive helicopters

00:21:14.750 --> 00:21:18.800 align:middle line:84%
that can tell which room
of your house you're in.

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:20.670 align:middle line:84%
So the right-wing
reactionaries who

00:21:20.670 --> 00:21:23.390 align:middle line:84%
said that they'd be tracking
us through our Social Security

00:21:23.390 --> 00:21:25.930 align:middle line:90%
numbers were right after all.

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:28.579 align:middle line:84%
So don't ignore anybody
just because their politics

00:21:28.579 --> 00:21:29.620 align:middle line:90%
are different than yours.

00:21:29.620 --> 00:21:31.131 align:middle line:90%
They might have a point.

00:21:31.131 --> 00:21:31.630 align:middle line:90%
Maybe.

00:21:31.630 --> 00:21:37.820 align:middle line:90%


00:21:37.820 --> 00:21:44.340 align:middle line:84%
Nasreddin was hired once to
bring 10 donkeys to the market.

00:21:44.340 --> 00:21:46.245 align:middle line:84%
So he got on one of
the donkeys and led

00:21:46.245 --> 00:21:48.720 align:middle line:84%
the other 9 ahead of him,
and started to the market.

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:50.550 align:middle line:84%
And after about an
hour, he got worried

00:21:50.550 --> 00:21:53.580 align:middle line:84%
that he might have lost
a donkey, so he counted.

00:21:53.580 --> 00:21:56.180 align:middle line:90%
And there were only 9.

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:59.190 align:middle line:84%
So he got off to look
around for the other donkey.

00:21:59.190 --> 00:22:01.970 align:middle line:84%
And he kept patting each donkey
as he walked around till he

00:22:01.970 --> 00:22:04.170 align:middle line:90%
found all 10 of them again.

00:22:04.170 --> 00:22:07.940 align:middle line:84%
And he got on the donkey
and started riding again.

00:22:07.940 --> 00:22:10.210 align:middle line:84%
And after another hour, he
got a bit worried again,

00:22:10.210 --> 00:22:12.440 align:middle line:90%
so he started counting.

00:22:12.440 --> 00:22:14.790 align:middle line:90%
Only 9.

00:22:14.790 --> 00:22:18.460 align:middle line:84%
So he got off his donkey and
walked around, feeling them

00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:19.740 align:middle line:90%
by the sides, patting them.

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:22.110 align:middle line:90%
And there were 10 donkeys again.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:23.180 align:middle line:90%
So he got back on.

00:22:23.180 --> 00:22:25.940 align:middle line:84%
This is the disappearing
donkey trick again

00:22:25.940 --> 00:22:28.800 align:middle line:90%
in a different form.

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:30.570 align:middle line:84%
And the next time he
found there were 9,

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:33.060 align:middle line:84%
he had to get off, and walk
around, and count them again

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:33.575 align:middle line:90%
on foot.

00:22:33.575 --> 00:22:35.060 align:middle line:90%
And there were 10 again.

00:22:35.060 --> 00:22:36.850 align:middle line:84%
So around the middle
of the afternoon,

00:22:36.850 --> 00:22:40.140 align:middle line:84%
he arrived at the market,
driving 9 donkeys behind him

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:43.490 align:middle line:84%
and carrying 1
donkey on his back.

00:22:43.490 --> 00:22:47.180 align:middle line:84%
That always gets a bigger
laugh than the first one.

00:22:47.180 --> 00:22:50.030 align:middle line:84%
Well, when I ask people to
describe the hall outside,

00:22:50.030 --> 00:22:51.500 align:middle line:90%
they never include themselves.

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:52.880 align:middle line:90%
They never include the observer.

00:22:52.880 --> 00:22:56.740 align:middle line:84%
That's another variation of
the disappearing donkey trick.

00:22:56.740 --> 00:22:59.400 align:middle line:84%
The kind of science that
everybody at new age

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:01.730 align:middle line:84%
conferences rants
and raves against

00:23:01.730 --> 00:23:06.030 align:middle line:84%
and denounces, so-called
Newtonian Descartian science.

00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:10.930 align:middle line:84%
Hasn't been taken seriously by
scientists for over 100 years.

00:23:10.930 --> 00:23:15.570 align:middle line:84%
With [INAUDIBLE] theorized
of quantum mechanics,

00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:17.660 align:middle line:84%
science has become
aware, especially

00:23:17.660 --> 00:23:21.820 align:middle line:84%
physics, has become aware
of what Buddhism has always

00:23:21.820 --> 00:23:24.590 align:middle line:84%
told us, you can't
leave out the observer.

00:23:24.590 --> 00:23:27.080 align:middle line:84%
Any separation between the
observer and the observed

00:23:27.080 --> 00:23:29.770 align:middle line:90%
introduces tremendous fallacies.

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:31.830 align:middle line:84%
That's another reason
for putting in the maybe.

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:33.980 align:middle line:84%
When you leave out
the maybe, you're

00:23:33.980 --> 00:23:35.950 align:middle line:84%
assuming that your
nervous system,

00:23:35.950 --> 00:23:38.990 align:middle line:84%
your brain, your
sensory apparatus

00:23:38.990 --> 00:23:41.570 align:middle line:84%
is apprehending
the whole universe.

00:23:41.570 --> 00:23:43.160 align:middle line:84%
Which is rather
an unlikely thing.

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:46.540 align:middle line:84%
Do you think you can swallow the
whole universe in your stomach?

00:23:46.540 --> 00:23:49.540 align:middle line:84%
Do you think you could inject
all the blood of the human race

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:52.170 align:middle line:84%
into your veins
without exploding?

00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:56.340 align:middle line:84%
Do you really think your brain
can contain the whole universe?

00:23:56.340 --> 00:23:58.090 align:middle line:84%
That's another reason
for putting a maybe

00:23:58.090 --> 00:24:01.080 align:middle line:90%
on most of your statements.

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:04.100 align:middle line:84%
Because everybody knows
things you don't know,

00:24:04.100 --> 00:24:07.880 align:middle line:84%
and everything you think you
know is really only a maybe.

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:10.395 align:middle line:84%
Now Korzybski in
1933 recommended

00:24:10.395 --> 00:24:14.220 align:middle line:90%
an infinite-valued logic.

00:24:14.220 --> 00:24:17.840 align:middle line:84%
I have found, in trying to
teach this to audiences,

00:24:17.840 --> 00:24:19.530 align:middle line:84%
that people's
minds go blank when

00:24:19.530 --> 00:24:22.110 align:middle line:90%
you say infinite-valued logic.

00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:24.640 align:middle line:84%
So I reduced it to
a 10-valued logic.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:26.830 align:middle line:90%
That's much easier to deal with.

00:24:26.830 --> 00:24:28.500 align:middle line:84%
You can extend it to
infinity if you've

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:30.740 align:middle line:84%
got enough decimal places
and enough instruments

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:32.715 align:middle line:84%
to make enough
delicate readings.

00:24:32.715 --> 00:24:37.500 align:middle line:84%
Everyday affairs, you can
reduce it to a 10-valued logic.

00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:38.490 align:middle line:90%
A 0 to 10.

00:24:38.490 --> 00:24:40.355 align:middle line:84%
That's actually
an 11-valued logic

00:24:40.355 --> 00:24:42.565 align:middle line:84%
since I just
included the 0 in it.

00:24:42.565 --> 00:24:45.560 align:middle line:84%
The 0, you put in everything
you're absolutely sure

00:24:45.560 --> 00:24:49.360 align:middle line:84%
has been totally refuted
and can't possibly be true.

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:51.850 align:middle line:84%
Most of that will turn
out to be true later on.

00:24:51.850 --> 00:24:54.275 align:middle line:84%
But what the hell,
we're talking about life

00:24:54.275 --> 00:24:56.320 align:middle line:84%
in time in which we
were not thinking

00:24:56.320 --> 00:24:59.200 align:middle line:84%
about evolution and further
discoveries and so on.

00:24:59.200 --> 00:25:02.040 align:middle line:84%
In 10, you put in everything
absolutely sure has been proven

00:25:02.040 --> 00:25:06.130 align:middle line:84%
and can never be refuted,
like Newtonian gravity,

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:07.760 align:middle line:90%
for instance.

00:25:07.760 --> 00:25:09.800 align:middle line:84%
Oh, no, that's been
refuted by Einstein.

00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:10.940 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:25:10.940 --> 00:25:12.770 align:middle line:84%
Well, the general
theory of relativity.

00:25:12.770 --> 00:25:15.880 align:middle line:84%
No, Hawking is working
on revising that.

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:18.220 align:middle line:84%
Well anyway, in between
the 0 and the 10,

00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:21.846 align:middle line:84%
you've got 9 other
places-- 1 to 9.

00:25:21.846 --> 00:25:26.170 align:middle line:84%
And just imagine if people
had the philosophy of maybe.

00:25:26.170 --> 00:25:29.310 align:middle line:84%
To take an example
it seems, I think,

00:25:29.310 --> 00:25:35.960 align:middle line:84%
less emotional and
dogmatically key than most,

00:25:35.960 --> 00:25:38.890 align:middle line:84%
one that people don't actually
attack each other with axes

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:42.490 align:middle line:90%
over-- the Loch Ness monster.

00:25:42.490 --> 00:25:48.950 align:middle line:84%
Now under the present
Indo-European speaking peoples,

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:52.040 align:middle line:84%
due to the Indo-European
subject-predicate structure

00:25:52.040 --> 00:25:55.380 align:middle line:84%
and the either-or logic
that derives from that,

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:58.330 align:middle line:84%
generally divide into people who
say I believe in the Loch Ness

00:25:58.330 --> 00:26:02.160 align:middle line:84%
monster, and I don't believe
in the Loch Ness monster.

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:05.270 align:middle line:84%
But in my 11-valued
logic, which I mistakenly

00:26:05.270 --> 00:26:08.990 align:middle line:84%
called 10-valued logic because
maybe I'm not fully awake yet.

00:26:08.990 --> 00:26:13.470 align:middle line:90%


00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:15.770 align:middle line:84%
Since we don't have
accurate scientific data,

00:26:15.770 --> 00:26:19.350 align:middle line:84%
I'm using subjective
estimates of probabilities.

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:23.010 align:middle line:84%
I would rate the Loch
Ness monster at about 6.

00:26:23.010 --> 00:26:25.440 align:middle line:84%
Which is to say that I feel
enough people have seen

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:28.280 align:middle line:84%
something floating around
in Loch Ness over a period

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:29.380 align:middle line:90%
of a couple hundred years.

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:31.255 align:middle line:84%
So there's probably
something floating around

00:26:31.255 --> 00:26:35.430 align:middle line:84%
in Loch Ness besides
ordinary fishy wishies

00:26:35.430 --> 00:26:38.050 align:middle line:90%
and guppies and whatnot.

00:26:38.050 --> 00:26:39.620 align:middle line:90%
But I'm not 100% sure.

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:41.946 align:middle line:84%
And most people think if
you give up being 100% sure,

00:26:41.946 --> 00:26:44.100 align:middle line:84%
if you don't have a
definite yes and no, you're

00:26:44.100 --> 00:26:46.580 align:middle line:84%
floating in an abyss
of uncertainties

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:48.060 align:middle line:90%
from which you'll never escape.

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:49.893 align:middle line:84%
But when you start
putting probabilities on,

00:26:49.893 --> 00:26:51.700 align:middle line:84%
you find a lot of
things have a 9.

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:53.570 align:middle line:90%
You put them at least at 9.

00:26:53.570 --> 00:26:56.525 align:middle line:84%
I feel I'd give a 9
rating to the probability

00:26:56.525 --> 00:27:02.690 align:middle line:84%
that the sun is going to seem
to rise tomorrow morning again.

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:05.200 align:middle line:84%
Of course, everybody knows
the sun doesn't really rise.

00:27:05.200 --> 00:27:07.080 align:middle line:90%
It's just the Earth rotating.

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:09.160 align:middle line:84%
But we still have this
Neolithic language,

00:27:09.160 --> 00:27:11.170 align:middle line:90%
so we talk about the sun rising.

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:12.320 align:middle line:90%
So that's what I mean.

00:27:12.320 --> 00:27:15.360 align:middle line:84%
I think there's over
a 9% probability

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:18.120 align:middle line:84%
that I expect that we'll
see the sun again tomorrow,

00:27:18.120 --> 00:27:21.270 align:middle line:84%
whether we see it rising,
or whether we stop and think

00:27:21.270 --> 00:27:22.450 align:middle line:90%
the sun isn't rising.

00:27:22.450 --> 00:27:24.085 align:middle line:84%
The Earth is rotating,
or revolving,

00:27:24.085 --> 00:27:27.900 align:middle line:90%
or orbiting around the sun.

00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:31.030 align:middle line:84%
So some things have a
very high probability.

00:27:31.030 --> 00:27:34.120 align:middle line:84%
Some thing's have a
very low probability.

00:27:34.120 --> 00:27:37.830 align:middle line:84%
I was speaking to the Irish
Science Fiction Society

00:27:37.830 --> 00:27:39.500 align:middle line:90%
a few years ago.

00:27:39.500 --> 00:27:41.970 align:middle line:84%
And in the question
period, somebody asked me,

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:44.325 align:middle line:90%
do you believe in UFOs?

00:27:44.325 --> 00:27:46.695 align:middle line:84%
And instead of going
into my maybe logic,

00:27:46.695 --> 00:27:49.864 align:middle line:84%
and 10-valued
logic, and so on, I

00:27:49.864 --> 00:27:51.530 align:middle line:84%
felt, that's a
straightforward question.

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:53.155 align:middle line:84%
I'll give him a
straightforward answer.

00:27:53.155 --> 00:27:54.730 align:middle line:90%
I said, yes, of course.

00:27:54.730 --> 00:27:57.450 align:middle line:84%
So he went off into a
tirade to the effect

00:27:57.450 --> 00:28:03.080 align:middle line:84%
that all UFOs were
sun dogs, which

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:07.210 align:middle line:84%
are heat inversions caused by
the mixture of water and oxygen

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:10.370 align:middle line:84%
in the atmosphere, which creates
strange glints in the air.

00:28:10.370 --> 00:28:13.960 align:middle line:84%
When he finally ran down,
I said, well, we agree.

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:15.989 align:middle line:84%
We both believe
in UFOs, only you

00:28:15.989 --> 00:28:18.405 align:middle line:84%
think you know what they are,
and I'm still a bit puzzled.

00:28:18.405 --> 00:28:21.385 align:middle line:90%


00:28:21.385 --> 00:28:23.510 align:middle line:84%
Which is very strange
because when most people talk

00:28:23.510 --> 00:28:25.490 align:middle line:84%
about UFOs, they
either believe in them

00:28:25.490 --> 00:28:27.440 align:middle line:90%
or they don't believe in them.

00:28:27.440 --> 00:28:32.140 align:middle line:84%
And yet, I don't see how anybody
could possibly deny them.

00:28:32.140 --> 00:28:33.482 align:middle line:90%
What does UFO mean?

00:28:33.482 --> 00:28:35.190 align:middle line:84%
Most people have
forgotten what it means.

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:37.865 align:middle line:84%
It means Unidentified
Flying Objects.

00:28:37.865 --> 00:28:42.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, I see three UFOs every
week, at least, at minimum.

00:28:42.890 --> 00:28:45.590 align:middle line:84%
I happen to have a very
nice balcony where I live,

00:28:45.590 --> 00:28:47.000 align:middle line:90%
with a view of Monterey Bay.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:50.765 align:middle line:84%
And I love to sit out there when
I'm not working at my computer.

00:28:50.765 --> 00:28:53.260 align:middle line:84%
I love to sit out on the
balcony and look at the view.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:55.520 align:middle line:84%
I've written more haiku
since I moved there

00:28:55.520 --> 00:28:58.900 align:middle line:84%
than I have in my
whole life before.

00:28:58.900 --> 00:29:00.630 align:middle line:84%
And it's not because
my health care

00:29:00.630 --> 00:29:02.400 align:middle line:90%
worker happens to be Japanese.

00:29:02.400 --> 00:29:05.090 align:middle line:84%
She doesn't even know
I'm writing haiku.

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:08.100 align:middle line:84%
I'm writing haiku because
they seem the appropriate form

00:29:08.100 --> 00:29:10.770 align:middle line:84%
to describe the views you
see from three floors up,

00:29:10.770 --> 00:29:11.850 align:middle line:90%
looking at Monterey Bay.

00:29:11.850 --> 00:29:13.130 align:middle line:90%
The view keeps changing.

00:29:13.130 --> 00:29:17.282 align:middle line:84%
It's never twice the same
from one hour to the next.

00:29:17.282 --> 00:29:20.060 align:middle line:84%
As a matter of fact, I
could condense all my haiku

00:29:20.060 --> 00:29:23.520 align:middle line:84%
into two words in
Greek-- rhei panta.

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:25.810 align:middle line:84%
Which is probably the
wrong pronunciation,

00:29:25.810 --> 00:29:28.410 align:middle line:90%
but it's the right letters.

00:29:28.410 --> 00:29:31.600 align:middle line:84%
That was said by
Heraclitus-- all things flow.

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:34.940 align:middle line:84%
Not only does Monterey flow,
but whether the dolphins

00:29:34.940 --> 00:29:38.100 align:middle line:84%
are there that day or not,
that changes over time.

00:29:38.100 --> 00:29:39.900 align:middle line:84%
Whether I could see
Monterrey or not

00:29:39.900 --> 00:29:43.660 align:middle line:84%
changes depending on how
much fog we've got that day.

00:29:43.660 --> 00:29:45.400 align:middle line:84%
So the view keeps
changing, so I keep

00:29:45.400 --> 00:29:49.070 align:middle line:84%
writing more haiku to express
my impressions of the changing

00:29:49.070 --> 00:29:49.570 align:middle line:90%
views.

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:52.930 align:middle line:90%


00:29:52.930 --> 00:29:56.130 align:middle line:84%
And I see at least
three UFOs every week,

00:29:56.130 --> 00:29:58.190 align:middle line:90%
especially around twilight.

00:29:58.190 --> 00:30:01.380 align:middle line:84%
I see even more of them
after it gets dark.

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:03.370 align:middle line:84%
This does not
particularly impress me

00:30:03.370 --> 00:30:06.720 align:middle line:84%
because I'm not quick to
identify things anyway.

00:30:06.720 --> 00:30:10.270 align:middle line:84%
I see at least seven
UNFOs every week.

00:30:10.270 --> 00:30:13.950 align:middle line:84%
That's Unidentified
Non-Flying Objects.

00:30:13.950 --> 00:30:15.810 align:middle line:84%
They go by on the
street so fast,

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:17.310 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what
the hell they are.

00:30:17.310 --> 00:30:20.530 align:middle line:90%


00:30:20.530 --> 00:30:24.420 align:middle line:84%
I saw a guy without arms
going by just a couple of days

00:30:24.420 --> 00:30:26.850 align:middle line:90%
ago on a bicycle.

00:30:26.850 --> 00:30:30.010 align:middle line:84%
I think maybe it
was a guy with arms,

00:30:30.010 --> 00:30:34.130 align:middle line:84%
only he was holding them down
to test his ability to steer

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:35.405 align:middle line:90%
without using the handlebars.

00:30:35.405 --> 00:30:37.100 align:middle line:90%
But I'm not sure.

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:40.790 align:middle line:84%
He's another unidentified
non-flying object.

00:30:40.790 --> 00:30:42.850 align:middle line:84%
It was either a guy
without arms or a guy

00:30:42.850 --> 00:30:45.060 align:middle line:84%
driving his bike
without using his arms.

00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:48.260 align:middle line:84%
I see weirder things
than that though.

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:51.950 align:middle line:84%
I saw a seagull land on
the roof across from me

00:30:51.950 --> 00:30:55.610 align:middle line:90%
with a silk top hat on.

00:30:55.610 --> 00:31:00.870 align:middle line:84%
And I just had my glasses
changed recently too.

00:31:00.870 --> 00:31:03.300 align:middle line:84%
The world is full of
unidentified objects

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:04.360 align:middle line:90%
as far as I'm concerned.

00:31:04.360 --> 00:31:06.915 align:middle line:84%
As a matter of fact, my
own wife was frequently

00:31:06.915 --> 00:31:10.540 align:middle line:84%
an unidentified object
at 3:00 in the morning.

00:31:10.540 --> 00:31:13.270 align:middle line:84%
When I get up to go to the
john at 3:00 in the morning,

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:16.890 align:middle line:84%
on my way back, I often
saw an unidentified object

00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:21.496 align:middle line:84%
approaching me down the
hall with the lights out.

00:31:21.496 --> 00:31:23.120 align:middle line:84%
It was only when she
got within 3 feet,

00:31:23.120 --> 00:31:24.980 align:middle line:84%
I would say, yeah,
that's my wife after all.

00:31:24.980 --> 00:31:28.540 align:middle line:84%
It's not a burglar or
anything sinister like that.

00:31:28.540 --> 00:31:31.490 align:middle line:84%
I'm surprised that people
identify so many objects

00:31:31.490 --> 00:31:32.260 align:middle line:90%
so easily.

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:35.295 align:middle line:84%
The world consists mostly,
at least partially,

00:31:35.295 --> 00:31:37.115 align:middle line:90%
of unidentified objects.

00:31:37.115 --> 00:31:52.020 align:middle line:90%


00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:57.725 align:middle line:84%
Professor Timothy FX Finnegan
of the Royal Sir Myles

00:31:57.725 --> 00:32:03.320 align:middle line:84%
nag Copaleen Astro-Anomalistic
Society in Dalkey, Ireland,

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:09.300 align:middle line:84%
sometime lecturer at Trinity
College, the founder of CSICON.

00:32:09.300 --> 00:32:12.230 align:middle line:84%
That's the Committee for
Surrealist Investigation

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:13.505 align:middle line:90%
of Claims of the Normal.

00:32:13.505 --> 00:32:17.730 align:middle line:90%


00:32:17.730 --> 00:32:20.800 align:middle line:84%
CSICON has a
million dollar offer

