00:37:56.320 --> 00:37:59.922 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to give you a
theory of modern history.

00:37:59.922 --> 00:38:04.350 align:middle line:84%
And please put it in the
maybe mold as much as you can.

00:38:04.350 --> 00:38:05.890 align:middle line:84%
Or as Aleister
Crowley used to say,

00:38:05.890 --> 00:38:11.250 align:middle line:84%
"Don't believe me, believe
your own common sense."

00:38:11.250 --> 00:38:15.630 align:middle line:84%
In 1945, General
Reinhard Gehlen,

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:19.390 align:middle line:84%
who was the chief of
the Soviet intelligence

00:38:19.390 --> 00:38:23.660 align:middle line:84%
section of Hitler's Secret
Service, as the American armies

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:26.210 align:middle line:84%
overran Germany,
General Reinhard

00:38:26.210 --> 00:38:28.800 align:middle line:84%
piled all the documents
he had about Soviet

00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:31.100 align:middle line:90%
Russia into a couple of trucks.

00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:34.670 align:middle line:84%
Drove them to an unknown
location and buried them.

00:38:34.670 --> 00:38:38.990 align:middle line:84%
And then drove to the
nearest American army troops

00:38:38.990 --> 00:38:42.240 align:middle line:84%
he could find and surrendered,
telling them what he had

00:38:42.240 --> 00:38:45.170 align:middle line:84%
and also telling them about
his connections in the Soviet

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:50.142 align:middle line:84%
Union, which included General
Vlasov of the Red Army, who

00:38:50.142 --> 00:38:53.200 align:middle line:84%
was a czarist who had
infiltrated the Red Army

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:57.390 align:middle line:84%
with a leader of a czarist
group within the communist

00:38:57.390 --> 00:39:00.650 align:middle line:84%
government, intent on
overturning the communists

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:03.810 align:middle line:90%
and restoring czarism.

00:39:03.810 --> 00:39:05.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, by the time
the word got back

00:39:05.670 --> 00:39:08.710 align:middle line:84%
to the Office of Strategic
Service, the forerunner

00:39:08.710 --> 00:39:14.595 align:middle line:84%
of the CIA, they for General
Gehlen out of his Nazi uniform

00:39:14.595 --> 00:39:17.710 align:middle line:84%
into an American
general's uniform.

00:39:17.710 --> 00:39:19.790 align:middle line:84%
He was flown back to
Washington, became

00:39:19.790 --> 00:39:22.730 align:middle line:84%
part of the US
Army intelligence.

00:39:22.730 --> 00:39:25.330 align:middle line:84%
Pretty soon, he was
transferred to the CIA

00:39:25.330 --> 00:39:27.490 align:middle line:90%
after that was created.

00:39:27.490 --> 00:39:29.220 align:middle line:84%
Went back to
Germany and ran what

00:39:29.220 --> 00:39:35.160 align:middle line:84%
was called the Gehlen Apparat,
which was in close contact

00:39:35.160 --> 00:39:37.710 align:middle line:84%
with General Vlasov
and other czarists

00:39:37.710 --> 00:39:40.460 align:middle line:90%
within the Soviet government.

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:46.560 align:middle line:84%
And so the presidents of the
United States from Truman,

00:39:46.560 --> 00:39:51.300 align:middle line:84%
Eisenhower onward,
Kennedy, Johnson,

00:39:51.300 --> 00:39:58.780 align:middle line:84%
and so on up through Reagan,
and George I, and Slick Willie,

00:39:58.780 --> 00:40:05.580 align:middle line:84%
and George II, His Royal
Fraudulency, all of them

00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:08.260 align:middle line:84%
were getting their basic
information about the Soviet

00:40:08.260 --> 00:40:11.130 align:middle line:84%
Union by way of a
Nazi general who

00:40:11.130 --> 00:40:15.490 align:middle line:84%
got his information from
czarists within Soviet Russia.

00:40:15.490 --> 00:40:17.780 align:middle line:84%
Which I think explains
why the rest of the world

00:40:17.780 --> 00:40:20.790 align:middle line:84%
gradually came to the conclusion
that American foreign policy

00:40:20.790 --> 00:40:23.780 align:middle line:90%
was batshit crazy.

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:27.150 align:middle line:84%
Nazis, and czarists, and
spooks, oh, my, as it

00:40:27.150 --> 00:40:31.180 align:middle line:90%
says in "The Wizard of Oz."

00:40:31.180 --> 00:40:33.760 align:middle line:84%
Well, more and more
American foreign policy

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:36.860 align:middle line:84%
was influenced by
czarism, until finally,

00:40:36.860 --> 00:40:41.260 align:middle line:84%
American domestic policy began
to be influenced by czarism.

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:44.120 align:middle line:84%
I've got a yoga exercise
for you like you've never

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:45.015 align:middle line:90%
heard of before.

00:40:45.015 --> 00:40:47.260 align:middle line:84%
And matter of fact, it's
not a yoga exercise at all.

00:40:47.260 --> 00:40:50.870 align:middle line:84%
I'm just calling it
that to intrigue you.

00:40:50.870 --> 00:40:52.640 align:middle line:90%
Go to your dictionary.

00:40:52.640 --> 00:40:56.470 align:middle line:84%
In the back of your dictionary,
any good-size dictionary,

00:40:56.470 --> 00:40:59.280 align:middle line:84%
they got a historical document
called the United States

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:01.040 align:middle line:90%
Constitution.

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:02.750 align:middle line:84%
They keep it in
print in dictionaries

00:41:02.750 --> 00:41:05.840 align:middle line:84%
as a historical
curiosity because it

00:41:05.840 --> 00:41:07.640 align:middle line:84%
has no relevance at
all to how the United

00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:10.980 align:middle line:90%
States is run these days.

00:41:10.980 --> 00:41:13.350 align:middle line:84%
After the main body
of the Constitution,

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:15.770 align:middle line:84%
then comes the first 10
amendments which are generally

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:17.840 align:middle line:90%
called the Bill of Rights.

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:19.170 align:middle line:90%
Read that.

00:41:19.170 --> 00:41:22.160 align:middle line:84%
Read it slowly, carefully,
and thoughtfully.

00:41:22.160 --> 00:41:25.780 align:middle line:84%
And see if any of those rights
are still guaranteed to us.

00:41:25.780 --> 00:41:28.770 align:middle line:84%
Every single one of them has
been nullified by one Supreme

00:41:28.770 --> 00:41:31.470 align:middle line:90%
Court or another.

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:34.880 align:middle line:84%
I'll just start
with the first one.

00:41:34.880 --> 00:41:38.480 align:middle line:84%
It says, "Congress shall make no
law abridging freedom of speech

00:41:38.480 --> 00:41:40.460 align:middle line:90%
or of the press."

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:45.110 align:middle line:84%
Now as Justice Black pointed
out in one of his dissents,

00:41:45.110 --> 00:41:47.830 align:middle line:84%
not only does "no" seem
to mean "no" in most

00:41:47.830 --> 00:41:51.680 align:middle line:84%
cases in the English language,
when people who are writing

00:41:51.680 --> 00:41:55.520 align:middle line:84%
happen to be literate, when
they write "no," they mean "no."

00:41:55.520 --> 00:41:59.050 align:middle line:84%
But we have plenty of evidence
in the letters, diaries,

00:41:59.050 --> 00:42:01.970 align:middle line:84%
and other writings of the
authors of the Constitution.

00:42:01.970 --> 00:42:04.700 align:middle line:84%
They were very
versatile, eloquent,

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:10.930 align:middle line:84%
and adept in the use
of style in language.

00:42:10.930 --> 00:42:13.735 align:middle line:84%
Like the Elizabethan age
was the great age of poetry

00:42:13.735 --> 00:42:16.930 align:middle line:84%
in the English language,
the late 18th century

00:42:16.930 --> 00:42:19.560 align:middle line:84%
was probably the greatest
age of prose we ever had.

00:42:19.560 --> 00:42:22.790 align:middle line:84%
We had more great prose
stylists at the end.

00:42:22.790 --> 00:42:26.690 align:middle line:84%
We had Gibbon, and Hume,
and Burke in England.

00:42:26.690 --> 00:42:28.420 align:middle line:84%
Oh, Burke came from
Ireland, actually.

00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:30.270 align:middle line:84%
Let's not give the
English credit for one

00:42:30.270 --> 00:42:35.700 align:middle line:84%
single Irishman
that they adopted.

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:39.520 align:middle line:84%
And over here, we had Jefferson,
and Adams, and Madison.

00:42:39.520 --> 00:42:43.560 align:middle line:84%
It was a fantastic age
for clear, crisp prose.

00:42:43.560 --> 00:42:46.990 align:middle line:84%
And so when they wrote "none,"
when they said "no laws,"

00:42:46.990 --> 00:42:50.090 align:middle line:84%
they almost certainly
meant no laws.

00:42:50.090 --> 00:42:52.710 align:middle line:84%
But if you want to be really
tricky, you might say,

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:54.720 align:middle line:84%
they left out a letter,
and they meant one law.

00:42:54.720 --> 00:43:00.760 align:middle line:84%
Congress shall establish one
law abridging freedom of speech.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:02.890 align:middle line:90%
That's quite a stretcher.

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:05.380 align:middle line:84%
But a good sophist,
somebody who studied logic

00:43:05.380 --> 00:43:08.475 align:middle line:84%
with the ancient Greeks and
philosophy with Plato and so

00:43:08.475 --> 00:43:10.840 align:middle line:84%
on, might be able to
put across an argument

00:43:10.840 --> 00:43:13.840 align:middle line:84%
that when they wrote "no
laws," they meant "one law."

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:17.520 align:middle line:84%
But Justice Black never
believed that because he said,

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:19.930 align:middle line:84%
"no laws," to me, seems
to mean "no laws."

00:43:19.930 --> 00:43:23.410 align:middle line:84%
Probably, the problem is I'm
still a farm boy at heart.

00:43:23.410 --> 00:43:25.230 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what my
problem is, but to me,

00:43:25.230 --> 00:43:28.540 align:middle line:90%
"no laws" means "no laws" too.

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:30.710 align:middle line:84%
But we not only have
a Supreme Court--

00:43:30.710 --> 00:43:36.050 align:middle line:84%
have had several Supreme
Courts over the last 200 years

00:43:36.050 --> 00:43:38.860 align:middle line:84%
which have decided that "no
laws" not only means "one law,"

00:43:38.860 --> 00:43:41.190 align:middle line:90%
it means "many laws."

00:43:41.190 --> 00:43:43.670 align:middle line:84%
We have many laws
abridging freedom of speech

00:43:43.670 --> 00:43:46.280 align:middle line:90%
and of the press.

00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:48.180 align:middle line:84%
What the hell happened
to the Bill of Rights?

00:43:48.180 --> 00:43:49.520 align:middle line:90%
That's only one clause.

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:51.910 align:middle line:84%
Read the rest of
the Bill of Rights.

00:43:51.910 --> 00:43:53.566 align:middle line:84%
See if any of the
things guaranteed

00:43:53.566 --> 00:43:55.065 align:middle line:84%
in the Bill of
Rights are still part

00:43:55.065 --> 00:43:57.580 align:middle line:90%
of the law in this country.

00:43:57.580 --> 00:44:00.070 align:middle line:84%
I read the whole damn
thing very carefully,

00:44:00.070 --> 00:44:02.990 align:middle line:90%
both straight and stoned.

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:05.052 align:middle line:84%
This is something I
learned from Timothy Leary.

00:44:05.052 --> 00:44:07.260 align:middle line:84%
If you want to understand
anything, read it straight,

00:44:07.260 --> 00:44:10.160 align:middle line:84%
then read it stoned, and
then read it straight again.

00:44:10.160 --> 00:44:12.610 align:middle line:90%
It's also the best way to write.

00:44:12.610 --> 00:44:15.140 align:middle line:84%
Write straight, then
rewrite stoned, and then

00:44:15.140 --> 00:44:17.850 align:middle line:90%
rewrite straight again.

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:19.950 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's the way
my prose is produced.

00:44:19.950 --> 00:44:21.660 align:middle line:84%
And I got a lot
of fans, so there

00:44:21.660 --> 00:44:23.714 align:middle line:84%
must be something in that
theory of composition.

00:44:23.714 --> 00:44:29.290 align:middle line:90%


00:44:29.290 --> 00:44:32.270 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm not saying the
Constitution is perfect.

00:44:32.270 --> 00:44:34.910 align:middle line:84%
The Constitution is
definitely flawed, especially

00:44:34.910 --> 00:44:36.770 align:middle line:90%
in relation to slavery.

00:44:36.770 --> 00:44:38.360 align:middle line:84%
But by and large,
the Constitution

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:41.430 align:middle line:84%
is a much better system
than what we've got now.

00:44:41.430 --> 00:44:51.800 align:middle line:90%


00:44:51.800 --> 00:44:53.620 align:middle line:84%
There's no place in
the Constitution,

00:44:53.620 --> 00:44:55.556 align:middle line:84%
by the way, where it
says that Congress

00:44:55.556 --> 00:44:56.930 align:middle line:84%
or any other branch
of government

00:44:56.930 --> 00:45:00.540 align:middle line:84%
should supervise our
medicine or our recreations.

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:02.880 align:middle line:84%
That's also totally
unconstitutional.

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:06.340 align:middle line:84%
But we got a czar in
charge of supervising both.

00:45:06.340 --> 00:45:09.210 align:middle line:84%
That's a result of General
Gehlen and the Gehlen Apparat,

00:45:09.210 --> 00:45:11.860 align:middle line:84%
and the gradual takeover
of our government.

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:14.210 align:middle line:84%
When the czarists took over
our government in the 1920s,

00:45:14.210 --> 00:45:15.900 align:middle line:84%
they didn't appoint
an official czar

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:18.110 align:middle line:90%
until the end of the 1980s.

00:45:18.110 --> 00:45:21.000 align:middle line:84%
But now they're coming out
in the open, more and more.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.950 align:middle line:84%
Now what a czar is
based on, Trotsky

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:26.550 align:middle line:84%
called it a combination
of European monarchism

00:45:26.550 --> 00:45:30.030 align:middle line:90%
and oriental despotism.

00:45:30.030 --> 00:45:32.720 align:middle line:84%
I think we've passed the
stage of European monarchism

00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:34.990 align:middle line:84%
and entered the stage
oriental despotism,

00:45:34.990 --> 00:45:39.460 align:middle line:84%
extreme right-wing
czarism during Bush I. Now

00:45:39.460 --> 00:45:43.630 align:middle line:84%
we're approaching total
oriental despotism.

00:45:43.630 --> 00:45:48.370 align:middle line:84%
>>I'd like to ask something,
but I would not like a maybe.

00:45:48.370 --> 00:45:52.065 align:middle line:84%
Regarding "The Illuminati,"
how much is it science fiction

00:45:52.065 --> 00:45:54.090 align:middle line:90%
and how much is it real?

00:45:54.090 --> 00:45:57.530 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's all
science fiction maybe.

00:45:57.530 --> 00:46:00.740 align:middle line:90%
And some of it is real maybe.

00:46:00.740 --> 00:46:02.840 align:middle line:84%
The original title
of "Illuminatus!"

00:46:02.840 --> 00:46:03.625 align:middle line:90%
was "Illuminatus!

00:46:03.625 --> 00:46:05.340 align:middle line:90%
A Head Test."

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:08.260 align:middle line:84%
And for some reason, Dell
took the subtitle off.

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:10.170 align:middle line:90%
I don't know why.

00:46:10.170 --> 00:46:13.370 align:middle line:84%
But the whole point is to make
the reader think for herself

00:46:13.370 --> 00:46:15.920 align:middle line:84%
or himself and decide
how much is real

00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:18.550 align:middle line:90%
and how much is science fiction.

00:46:18.550 --> 00:46:21.000 align:middle line:84%
And it would ruin the
whole game if I told you.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.590 align:middle line:90%
And besides, I can't tell you.

00:46:23.590 --> 00:46:26.470 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how much is
real and how much is fiction.

00:46:26.470 --> 00:46:32.490 align:middle line:84%
That's assuming I possessed the
objective, absolute authority

00:46:32.490 --> 00:46:36.390 align:middle line:84%
that 19th century novelist
all pretended to possess,

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:39.550 align:middle line:90%
the impersonal narrative voice.

00:46:39.550 --> 00:46:42.870 align:middle line:84%
And "Illuminatus!" does not have
one single impersonal narrative

00:46:42.870 --> 00:46:43.440 align:middle line:90%
voice in it.

00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:47.360 align:middle line:84%
It's got 101 narrators, all of
whom have different prejudices.

00:46:47.360 --> 00:46:48.800 align:middle line:84%
You've got to
decide for yourself

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:51.850 align:middle line:84%
which ones to trust if you're
going to trust any of them.

00:46:51.850 --> 00:46:53.310 align:middle line:90%
I didn't invent that technique.

00:46:53.310 --> 00:46:56.180 align:middle line:84%
Joyce used it in
"Ulysses," by the way.

00:46:56.180 --> 00:46:58.950 align:middle line:84%
I think it's the only way to
write a novel contemporary

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:01.560 align:middle line:84%
with our times in which
unanimity has entirely

00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:02.300 align:middle line:90%
disappeared.

00:47:02.300 --> 00:47:05.830 align:middle line:84%
Nobody believes in objectivity
anymore except Ayn Rand,

00:47:05.830 --> 00:47:07.120 align:middle line:90%
who was a speed freak.

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:10.730 align:middle line:90%


00:47:10.730 --> 00:47:13.770 align:middle line:84%
We're all very well aware
of neurological relativism,

00:47:13.770 --> 00:47:17.530 align:middle line:84%
whether we use that
word for it or not.

00:47:17.530 --> 00:47:19.800 align:middle line:84%
All of my books are
deliberately constructed so

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:21.440 align:middle line:84%
that the reader
can't [AUDIO OUT]

00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:22.890 align:middle line:90%
and when I'm telling the truth.

00:47:22.890 --> 00:47:27.530 align:middle line:84%
By the way, does anybody
know who Moishe Horwitz is?

00:47:27.530 --> 00:47:32.131 align:middle line:84%
He's the Face on Mars according
to Timothy FX Finnegan.

00:47:32.131 --> 00:47:32.630 align:middle line:90%
What?

00:47:32.630 --> 00:47:35.140 align:middle line:90%
What was the answer?

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:36.820 align:middle line:84%
Nobody knows who
Moishe Horwitz is.

00:47:36.820 --> 00:47:38.670 align:middle line:90%
Find out who Moishe Horwitz is.

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:41.380 align:middle line:84%
Then you'll figure out
whether I invented Timothy FX

00:47:41.380 --> 00:47:44.550 align:middle line:90%
Finnegan or he really exists.

00:47:44.550 --> 00:47:46.190 align:middle line:84%
And then you might
have a better chance

00:47:46.190 --> 00:47:49.410 align:middle line:84%
of figuring out what the hell
the Face on Mars really is.

00:47:49.410 --> 00:47:52.320 align:middle line:84%
If you believe the word "really"
means something and the word

00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:54.460 align:middle line:90%
"is" really means something.

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:56.275 align:middle line:84%
As far as I'm
concerned, I've never

00:47:56.275 --> 00:47:57.900 align:middle line:84%
found any use of the
word "is" where it

00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:00.505 align:middle line:90%
doesn't mean "it seems to me."

00:48:00.505 --> 00:48:02.880 align:middle line:84%
And yet, it confuses you into
thinking you're not talking

00:48:02.880 --> 00:48:04.500 align:middle line:90%
about your own reactions.

00:48:04.500 --> 00:48:08.390 align:middle line:84%
You're talking about
something quote "objective."

00:48:08.390 --> 00:48:09.820 align:middle line:90%
>>When's your next book?

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:11.500 align:middle line:84%
>>I don't know when
it's coming out.

00:48:11.500 --> 00:48:13.090 align:middle line:90%
I haven't finished it.

00:48:13.090 --> 00:48:18.496 align:middle line:84%
But it's called "The
Tale of the Tribe."

00:48:18.496 --> 00:48:21.750 align:middle line:84%
And it's a study of the
influence of Ezra Pound's

00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:24.310 align:middle line:84%
"Cantos" and James
Joyce's "Finnegans

00:48:24.310 --> 00:48:28.930 align:middle line:84%
Wake" on the communication
theories of Marshall McLuhan,

00:48:28.930 --> 00:48:32.440 align:middle line:84%
which he wrote way back in
the dark ages of television

00:48:32.440 --> 00:48:35.480 align:middle line:84%
in the 1960s, which
I think are coming

00:48:35.480 --> 00:48:39.000 align:middle line:84%
true on the internet
in the 21st century.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:42.850 align:middle line:84%
So it's about how Joyce
and Pound are our best

00:48:42.850 --> 00:48:46.400 align:middle line:84%
guides to the emerging
multicultural world we're

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:49.400 align:middle line:84%
entering in the 21st
century, in which we're

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:52.310 align:middle line:84%
going to have to learn to speak
to people from other cultures

00:48:52.310 --> 00:48:56.340 align:middle line:84%
and understand them, and
help them understand us too.

00:48:56.340 --> 00:48:58.760 align:middle line:84%
Which is why "Finnegans
Wake" and "The Cantos"

00:48:58.760 --> 00:49:02.060 align:middle line:84%
are written in 20
languages or more.

00:49:02.060 --> 00:49:05.740 align:middle line:84%
Because they are
attempts to communicate

00:49:05.740 --> 00:49:08.270 align:middle line:84%
across cultural
boundaries, which

00:49:08.270 --> 00:49:10.470 align:middle line:84%
is what internet is more
and more teaching us

00:49:10.470 --> 00:49:13.110 align:middle line:90%
we've got to do.

00:49:13.110 --> 00:49:16.411 align:middle line:84%
I'm all for globalization,
unlike most radicals.

00:49:16.411 --> 00:49:18.160 align:middle line:84%
I just want it to come
from the grassroots

00:49:18.160 --> 00:49:21.960 align:middle line:84%
up and not from the
Federal Reserve Board down.

00:49:21.960 --> 00:49:22.460 align:middle line:90%
>>Right on.

00:49:22.460 --> 00:49:24.885 align:middle line:90%
[APPLAUSE]

00:49:24.885 --> 00:49:27.320 align:middle line:84%
>>Ah, we got some
other people here

00:49:27.320 --> 00:49:29.580 align:middle line:84%
who don't trust the
Federal Reserve.

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:31.440 align:middle line:90%
That's good to know.

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:34.582 align:middle line:84%
>>I was wondering what you
think about modern models

00:49:34.582 --> 00:49:37.844 align:middle line:84%
of consciousness evolution, like
Wilber Spectrum psychologies

00:49:37.844 --> 00:49:42.880 align:middle line:84%
compared to the Eight-Circuit
models of the brain.

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:46.440 align:middle line:90%


00:49:46.440 --> 00:49:47.660 align:middle line:90%
>>Ken Wilber?

00:49:47.660 --> 00:49:49.400 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:49:49.400 --> 00:49:51.540 align:middle line:84%
I have worked out
a correspondence

00:49:51.540 --> 00:49:55.370 align:middle line:84%
between Ken Wilber's Spectrum,
Gurdjieff's Vibration Levels,

00:49:55.370 --> 00:49:56.790 align:middle line:90%
and Leary's Eight-Circuits.

00:49:56.790 --> 00:49:58.930 align:middle line:84%
I think they're all saying
the same thing in sets

00:49:58.930 --> 00:50:01.560 align:middle line:90%
of three different metaphors.

00:50:01.560 --> 00:50:05.690 align:middle line:84%
I prefer Leary's because
I've been thinking

00:50:05.690 --> 00:50:08.690 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the nervous
system rather than in terms

00:50:08.690 --> 00:50:13.090 align:middle line:84%
of more abstract
and ghostly entities

00:50:13.090 --> 00:50:16.720 align:middle line:84%
ever since I got interested
in general semantics

00:50:16.720 --> 00:50:19.380 align:middle line:90%
about 45 years ago.

00:50:19.380 --> 00:50:22.980 align:middle line:84%
So Leary's system seems
more natural to me,

00:50:22.980 --> 00:50:26.530 align:middle line:84%
which does not mean it's the
best system for everybody.

00:50:26.530 --> 00:50:28.470 align:middle line:84%
It's just I'm used to
thinking in terms of how

00:50:28.470 --> 00:50:32.870 align:middle line:84%
does my nervous system
respond to this?

00:50:32.870 --> 00:50:37.420 align:middle line:84%
But I think the eight
levels, whether you

00:50:37.420 --> 00:50:40.360 align:middle line:84%
want to call them eight
circuits or eight spectrums.

00:50:40.360 --> 00:50:43.610 align:middle line:84%
They're all in "Finnegans
Wake" too, by the way.

00:50:43.610 --> 00:50:46.520 align:middle line:84%
They go back to the seven
souls of the Egyptians

00:50:46.520 --> 00:50:50.600 align:middle line:84%
and the seven chakras of the
various Hindu and Buddhist

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:52.750 align:middle line:90%
systems.

00:50:52.750 --> 00:50:55.890 align:middle line:84%
I do think it's very easy
to make the distinction

00:50:55.890 --> 00:50:58.140 align:middle line:90%
between those levels.

00:50:58.140 --> 00:51:00.590 align:middle line:84%
And what language
you're going to use

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:02.690 align:middle line:84%
to discuss it depends
on what language makes

00:51:02.690 --> 00:51:04.710 align:middle line:84%
most sense to you,
and what language you

00:51:04.710 --> 00:51:09.140 align:middle line:84%
think will make most sense to
the audience you're talking to.

00:51:09.140 --> 00:51:11.910 align:middle line:84%
If I were addressing a
theosophical convention,

00:51:11.910 --> 00:51:14.470 align:middle line:90%
I'd use Ken Wilber's terms.

00:51:14.470 --> 00:51:18.366 align:middle line:84%
If I were addressing, as
I did a few years ago,

00:51:18.366 --> 00:51:19.865 align:middle line:84%
the Institute for
General Semantics,

00:51:19.865 --> 00:51:22.630 align:middle line:84%
I used Leary's
neurological terms.

00:51:22.630 --> 00:51:25.785 align:middle line:84%
It depends on who
you're talking to.

00:51:25.785 --> 00:51:29.620 align:middle line:84%
And I can use the Gurdjieff
system pretty well by now too

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:32.931 align:middle line:84%
if I happen to be talking
to a bunch of Fourth Wayers

00:51:32.931 --> 00:51:34.680 align:middle line:84%
or whatever they call
themselves nowadays.

00:51:34.680 --> 00:51:38.160 align:middle line:90%


00:51:38.160 --> 00:51:41.444 align:middle line:84%
Does that answer
your question, maybe?

00:51:41.444 --> 00:51:45.300 align:middle line:84%
>>I was wondering what you
think about the emerging

00:51:45.300 --> 00:51:49.570 align:middle line:84%
popularization of
transpersonal psychology.

00:51:49.570 --> 00:51:54.730 align:middle line:84%
Leary was saying the
same stuff 30 years ago.

00:51:54.730 --> 00:52:01.270 align:middle line:84%
And just how it affects
culture the same way.

00:52:01.270 --> 00:52:05.340 align:middle line:84%
Wilber is much more accepted
than Leary ever was.

00:52:05.340 --> 00:52:06.300 align:middle line:90%
>>Oh, well of course.

00:52:06.300 --> 00:52:07.470 align:middle line:90%
He's 100% acid-free.

00:52:07.470 --> 00:52:17.340 align:middle line:90%


00:52:17.340 --> 00:52:19.300 align:middle line:84%
Well, actually,
I'm more interested

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:21.030 align:middle line:84%
in transpirational
linguistics than

00:52:21.030 --> 00:52:23.140 align:middle line:90%
in transpirational psychology.

00:52:23.140 --> 00:52:25.370 align:middle line:84%
I know the people
at Berkeley who

00:52:25.370 --> 00:52:28.340 align:middle line:84%
invented transpirational
linguistics, which fits in

00:52:28.340 --> 00:52:31.720 align:middle line:84%
very well with Benjamin Lee
Whorf's metalinguistics,

00:52:31.720 --> 00:52:34.610 align:middle line:84%
Korzybski's general
semantics, and Bandler's

00:52:34.610 --> 00:52:37.140 align:middle line:90%
neurolinguistic programming.

00:52:37.140 --> 00:52:40.120 align:middle line:84%
I do believe we live
in mostly acceptance

00:52:40.120 --> 00:52:42.740 align:middle line:84%
for certain special
states of consciousness.

00:52:42.740 --> 00:52:45.430 align:middle line:84%
We live mostly in
a web of words.

00:52:45.430 --> 00:52:47.400 align:middle line:84%
And learning which
words control us

00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:51.180 align:middle line:84%
and how to take control
over the words seems--

00:52:51.180 --> 00:52:54.370 align:middle line:84%
The whole area that Korzybski
called neurosemantics

00:52:54.370 --> 00:52:57.720 align:middle line:84%
and Bandler called
neurolinguistics,

00:52:57.720 --> 00:52:59.680 align:middle line:84%
this seems to me
the most vital thing

00:52:59.680 --> 00:53:02.965 align:middle line:84%
to study because we're
communicating all the time.

00:53:02.965 --> 00:53:04.840 align:middle line:84%
Even when we're not
talking to somebody else,

00:53:04.840 --> 00:53:08.610 align:middle line:84%
we're communicating to ourselves
in words most of the time.

00:53:08.610 --> 00:53:11.020 align:middle line:84%
And to learn which
words are hypnotizing us

00:53:11.020 --> 00:53:13.110 align:middle line:84%
and which words
can dehypnotize us.

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:15.820 align:middle line:90%


00:53:15.820 --> 00:53:18.470 align:middle line:84%
Korzybski believed we
should all learn mathematics

00:53:18.470 --> 00:53:20.970 align:middle line:84%
to break the spell that
Indo-European has on

00:53:20.970 --> 00:53:24.330 align:middle line:84%
making us think of
actor-action, the thing

00:53:24.330 --> 00:53:27.140 align:middle line:84%
acted upon, which is not the
way the universe is constructed

00:53:27.140 --> 00:53:28.242 align:middle line:90%
at all.

00:53:28.242 --> 00:53:30.150 align:middle line:84%
And I used to go
around for years,

00:53:30.150 --> 00:53:32.872 align:middle line:84%
urging people to learn more
mathematics until I found out

00:53:32.872 --> 00:53:34.830 align:middle line:84%
that most people would
rather cut their throats

00:53:34.830 --> 00:53:36.981 align:middle line:90%
than try to study mathematics.

00:53:36.981 --> 00:53:38.680 align:middle line:90%
So now I found an easier way.

00:53:38.680 --> 00:53:41.670 align:middle line:84%
I just tell them
to study Chinese.

00:53:41.670 --> 00:53:43.694 align:middle line:84%
If you study Chinese
at all, you'll

00:53:43.694 --> 00:53:45.860 align:middle line:84%
find that doesn't have a
subject-predicate structure

00:53:45.860 --> 00:53:46.359 align:middle line:90%
either.

00:53:46.359 --> 00:53:48.250 align:middle line:90%
And every noun is a verb.

00:53:48.250 --> 00:53:50.890 align:middle line:84%
As Ernest Fenollosa
said in his essay,

00:53:50.890 --> 00:53:54.700 align:middle line:84%
"The Chinese Written Character
as a Medium for Poetry,"

00:53:54.700 --> 00:53:58.120 align:middle line:84%
"In ideogramic languages, the
verb and the noun are one.

00:53:58.120 --> 00:54:01.670 align:middle line:84%
Motion in things,
things in motion."

00:54:01.670 --> 00:54:04.160 align:middle line:84%
If Dr. Kaku is here,
I think he'd agree,

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:07.530 align:middle line:84%
